<br>
  If you have a solution or even a remotely good suggestion speak up, but spare us the moron level sarcastic commentary.  I personally stand in the middle of this subject, preferring a form of minimal socialized healthcare for the community as a whole, with more in-depth coverage for those that can afford it or wish to designate part of their income to that purpose.  Either add your input on why your side would be preferable, or go back to shutting the fuck up, because I'm starting to get Bled flashbacks. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1874<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/21/03 11:49 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Those Without Healthcare Obviously Don't Want It</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>You are SO right. There is no, NO ONE, in that income window where, after they pay for housing, food, power, and transportation, they don't have enough money left to pay for health care. No one we should care about, anyway...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If your income is really so low that you cannot afford health insurance, you'd qualify for Medicaid.  Perhaps the Medicaid income requirements are too low, if so we should raise them, not fuck over the rest of the system by lowering everyone else's quality of care.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>What about when efficiency comes at the price of human life and suffering? I'm sure it is often more efficient to let a person die rather than provide them care. There are some things in society that should not be left to the mercy of the free market.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The best way to relieve human suffering is to deliver the best quality care.  If we are efficient, we can deliver care to more people for less money.  If we are inefficient, we are wasting money on bureaucracy and government mismanagement.  Efficiency leads to greater coverage and a net reduction in human suffering, not the other way around.  Inefficiency leads to waste and leaves us with less money available to provide health care to those who need it.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1876<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/21/03 12:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Those Without Healthcare Obviously Don't Want It</span><hr size=1> I would support a system by which the government provided vouchers to people to purchase health insurance from a private carrier over socialized medicine.  That way people would maintain choice of carrier, and there would still be competition and thus efficiency.  People could put in extra money if they chose above the cost of the voucher to purchase premium insurance and get even better coverage.  I'm not really in favor of a national health care system on this scale, but something like this would be cheaper than socialized medicine, provide universal coverage, and provide vastly superior quality of care.  Keep the government out of it.<br>
<br>
Incidentally, such a program would cost about what we pay every year as interest on the national debt.<br>
<br>
If only the liberals in the past had not created programs that we could not afford, and had been more fiscally responsible, we would be able to afford such a program today.  Not to even mention all the pork in our budgets...<br>
<br>
