<br>
I know my first year outta school, I worked for 10.50/hr and could easily afford insurance even after car payment, rent and insurance, but I just opted not to budget it, instead spending the money on beer, video games and friday/saturday night out.<br>
<br>
  Most single people I would wager who don't have health insurance don't have it by choice, or by choice of how they budget their cash.  Now lower income families on the other hand should receive some sort of government assistance for medical care.  (Not sure if medicaid or care of whatever covers that)<br>
<br>
  My actual biggest problem with getting coverage later in life was the fact that since all of my work was contractor/consultant, it was near impossible to find reasonably priced healthcare unless I happened to be working for one of the bigger consulting firms at the time. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 1884<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/22/03 1:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=59>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Those Without Healthcare Obviously Don't Want It</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>... You know that the liberals in Canada are running a budget surplus, *AND* we have socialized health care? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Two problems with that.  First, your healthcare system sucks ass.  For the second, see Ayiar's photo essay on the Canadian military.  If we didn't have to take care of the whole fucking world cause everyone else is too fucking lazy to do so, we wouldn't need to carry a $400 billion military budget.  That's probably more than Canada's entire budget.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>FFS, I'm working 2 jobs for a total of 11.5 hours a day (yes gimp jobs, but both white collar) and I can't afford health care for myself let alone an entire family.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Sorry but not buying this at all.  I'm with Ayiar on this one.  You pay for eq.  I bet you have a car.  What kind of car is it?  You could have bought a $3000 budget model through the classified and not had a car payment.  Where do you live?  How much do you pay in rent?  How about entertainment?  How many movies have you gone to this year?  How many times have you gone out to dinner?  Do you have cable television?  The computer you own could have been 1-2 years of health insurance.  None of this stuff is necessity.  (Rent is, but probably not at the level you are paying for it now.)  The point is that I have no problem with people having to give up luxuries in order to purchase health insurance, AND I have no problem with them deciding that because they are in good health, they want to roll the dice and have those luxuries instead of insurance.  I don't want to pay more taxes to subsidize someone's entertainment budget or get them a nicer car.  If you are going to tell me that a single mom can't afford to purchase basic food and shelter for her family if she buys medical insurance, now I have sympathy.  No cable TV?  Oh well, live with it.  I'm not working so you can watch Oprah.  Also, does your wife work?  In some families, both parents have to work to support the family.  That's just how it is.  A single policy is in the neigborhood of $1200 a year for a healthy person, that's not much at all.  There are tax benefits too.  Additionally, if you are low income, there are all kinds of government subsidized plans that cost a lot less.<br>
<br>
My parents were really fucking poor when I was born.  We had basically no money.  My dad was a struggling opera singer and worked as an assistant manager in Stars department stores.  My mother didn't work as my sister and I had just been born.  My parents always found a way to purchase health insurance.  It might have meant my dad mowed lawns for the neighbors.  He drove a 16 year old Datsun with metal plates riveted onto the sides to cover up the rust holes and plastic for windows.  It meant no vacations, no cable TV, no eating out, etc.  It was a matter of priorities, health insurance was the first priority.  You'd be amazed how many people could afford it if they really wanted to.  However, it involves making some sacrifices.<br>
<br>
There are a few people in our society who really can't afford health insurance.  These people are not common.  The reason is that the poorest of the poor in our society qualify for Medicaid, so the very bottom is taken care of.  The top is obviously taken care of because they can afford health care.  The problem is what some refer to as the &quot;working poor,&quot; a group of people that are just above the Medicaid cap but are still really struggling to survive.  One way to deal with this problem is to raise the income caps for Medicaid to include more people in the program.<br>
<br>
I'd prefer to destroy the entire Medicaid program and use a voucher system by which they purchase care in the private sector.  I'd do the same with Medicare.  Fortunately, Bush is actually starting to privatize Medicare.  In the latest bill, seniors will have the option of enrolling in private coverage at no extra cost to them instead of Medicare.  I think that we are going to see an increased privatization of Medicare/Medicaid in the future, which will help a lot with cost control and provide superior care.  Even if we maintain Medicare as an option, the competition will be great for the system's efficiency and quality of care.<br>
<br>
